  "prompt": "How does the ozone layer filter out the ultraviolet rays?",
  "response": "The ozone layer, located in the stratosphere about 10-50 kilometers above Earth's surface, filters out harmful ultraviolet (UV) radiation through a specific chemical process:\n\n1. Ozone composition:\n- Consists of three oxygen atoms (O3)\n- Naturally occurring in the stratosphere\n\n2. UV radiation absorption:\n- Ozone molecules absorb different types of UV radiation (UV-A, UV-B, and UV-C)\n- Most effective at blocking UV-B and UV-C rays, which are the most harmful to living organisms\n\n3. Chemical interaction:\n- When UV radiation hits an ozone molecule, it breaks the molecular bond\n- This process converts the UV radiation into heat\n- The ozone molecule is temporarily split into oxygen molecules (O2) and a single oxygen atom\n\n4. Regeneration:\n- The separated oxygen atoms quickly recombine with other oxygen molecules\n- This process continuously reforms ozone molecules\n- Creates a continuous cycle of UV radiation filtering\n\n5. Protection mechanism:\n- Prevents most harmful UV radiation from reaching Earth's surface\n- Protects living organisms from potential DNA damage and other harmful effects\n\nThis natural filtering process is crucial for protecting life on Earth from dangerous solar radiation.",
